The pace of these asanas is a bit too fast actually. A beginner like me finds it difficult to do the plank or downward dog as easily as it is shown.
Secondly, what does it even mean to shift weight to your fingertips!? I mean, when I am in cat-cow, my wrists are like cemented into the ground. It feels impossible to move them. Moreover, the video just rushes quickly ahead without providing time to adjust.

I was unclear about my intentions in the beginning but I am broadcasting them here after the practice:
1. Limit the judgement. There is a preconceived judgement about everything, every action that I see on the screen. Like this is so weird, what if someone walks into my room while I am doing these weird poses!?
2. Disconnecting the intellect from the body. The overthinking just hangs you up taking control of your body and you find yourself surrendering to your mind. If you are doing something to better yourself, that practice ain't good.

I couldn't do this when it first came out live because I had severe headache and wasn't prepared. Yesterday while I was walking back home from work, I felt like crying so bad there was this massive build up of energy all of a sudden I felt VERY emotional. As I reached home, I was in the shower sobbing, I don't even know why it could be from my headache or stress or maybe emotions I needed to release that I was holding myself back from feeling them. I cried for a good straight 20 minutes and it felt very relieving. I've never cried like that in so long. I wasn't even thinking "what if someone heard me" I was completely surrendering and being there for myself. I don't want to exegerrate but it felt like something was coming out from my body and leaving. It felt like something was sitting on my throat and chest. Today, although I still feel tired and headache and have funny puffy eyes I decided to hop on the mat. I didn't do the downward dog and modified some poses but I feel good now that I am on this journey AGAIN with you and the rest of the community. To anyone reading this, just a reminder to be with your emotions and don't be shy to express specially sadness because its a part of being human. Be there for yourself. Be there for yourself like you're there for someone when their sick. Never feel embarrassed to ask for help and say "I am not okay", something I am learning to do. Wow! I am very aware that I wrote so much. Sheesh. Anyways, I send you all so much love and light. Namaste. Thank you Adriene. My hero <3

Adrienne, you do so much for your viewers by providing a guided peaceful stretching session, but why don't you do anything for the Hindus whom which yoga is stolen from? There is no mention of the religious meaning of yoga in your videos and I find that to be a bit weird. Is it perhaps insulting in a way to not give credit to Hinduism while simultaneously explaining to viewers that yoga is the religious lifestyle of Hinduism? Covertly pushing religion is unethical, as is stealing a religious practice and pretending it's secular to disguise its true meaning in order to sell it to people who don't identify as religious. Hopefully those diving into "yoga" for the first time see this before they get caught up in this big beast of a business that has completely distorted this practice in the west. Your youtube series if often mentioned to me when I mention the problems of yoga in the West, which I find very ironic being that you are influencing 10.6 million subscribers with the colonized delusion of Western "yoga", not actual yoga.

One year ago, I started Breath, my first 30day yoga journey. I have been practicing almost consistently ever since. It amazes me to see how far I have come over the past year - I have gained flexibility and strength, but more importantly, Yoga and Adriene have changed my attitude towards life. I remember these gems which I often bring up in my daily life-
- It is okay to fail. We can always, always begin again. There is no shame or guilt in that. 
- When overwhelmed, just breathe and start again with what's in your control.
-Don't worry about the results, just be mindful and enjoy the process.
- There is always something to be grateful for, especially the privileges that we take for granted. When I practice gratitude, sometimes even as small as to be able to take a full deep breath in, it puts my mind in a positive space and helps me keep myself grounded.
I am deeply thankful for Yoga with Adriene and this amazing community to help me be stronger and more resilient, physically as well as mentally. Thank you from the bottom of my heart üôè

My sister has been doing yoga for 15 years and suggested that I try it and gave me several books to read and recommend this channel. The last few weeks has been me trying to learn and get flexibility back. I know I will never be fully fixed but I am going to try, thank you for the videos, it's something to do after work, thank you.

Something happened that I did not expect. As I layed in shavasana I sensed myself present more than I have been lately...and I felt The Presence. Move...its time to move...from places where we grew-up as children, some of us are still there not knowing how to move pass the pain. But, MOVE is going to guide us through. Thank you Adriene for being such a sensitive vessel. Thank you for taking us with you on your own journey. This 30 Day Yoga Journey feels climactic, like it was all leading to this. 3 years ago I started my first 30 days of Yoga and I remember thinking that I'd never finish but why not give it a go and see how far I get. My first weeks were filled with moments where I almost gave up. I spent many poses angrily cursing Adriene's name as I forced myself into positions I wasn't ready for and stayed longer than my body wanted me to. Even just sitting upright was a challenge. Why was this so hard? Fast forward to today, I'm not feeling great this morning so I take it easy on a few poses and end a few early. Why force myself into a position that isn't going to benefit me today? As I relax in child's pose for a moment I think to myself was this new mindset the key to all my recent progress? I think so, and I can't help but wonder how much time I wasted letting my ego get in the way of me moving forward? Am I doing this in other areas of my life? Might be time to reevaluate a few things.

For me, yoga or any physical activity is really tough to bring myself to do. I really struggle with self worth and feeling enough. Doing anything that highlights the weakness I feel in my own body causes me to feel frightened and scared: It causes me to face myself and I don't really love what I see. However, every year I try to commit to these 30 days of yoga and I hope that this year, maybe I can last the duration. Because when I do these yoga practices, when I cn hear someone with me in the dark,  I feel like I can manage the fear and the panic just long enough to feel pride and hope in and for myself. To anyone else like me, I believe that we can accomplish this and that we are worth more than we know or think. Put aside what others might be thinking, take a breath and feel at home in yourself. You are valuable and you are worthy of your own love: take it with both hands.

Dear Adriene 1st things first! Thank you for putting yourself out there, showing up for others, sharing your loving kindness and generosity of spirit beyond what the mind's eye could ever imagine. You are amazing! Please allow those words to land in your heart center, from my heart to yours.
My journey with Yoga began many moons ago, in 2001. Fast Forward to 2020, numbers in the past meant to me having perfect vision, but that was before the Covid-19 Pandemic Outbreak brought so many of us to our knees, changing our lives forever. 

I remember being the last student walking out the door as the owner who i adored was locking up the evening I finished my yoga practice. The Studio became my sacred place, one that i would return to again and again over the next 7 years, becoming in time well spent, my safe place, my home away from home. 
I discovered in that time a community of the most loving and kind down to earth people I had found to share my practice with from 2013- March of 2020. The Day our beloved Yoga Studio closed its doors for the very last time. 
Fast forward to today. My1st day returning to my mat since the Pandemic changed life as  so many of us thought we knew it. 

My yoga mat has weathered with me through many, many storms, since i first set my mat down to practice  almost 2 decades ago. My oftentimes mindful and just as often thoughtless folding and unfolding of so many tightly wrapped up unresolved memories and emotions. 
I never knew before I began my journey within the practice of Yoga, there was so much more to the practice than meets the eye. I had stored deep within my tissues so many unresolved issues, locked up over 68 years of living, learning, giving, taking, holding, clinging, loving, laughter and tears. 

I am in many ways, the same person when it gets right down to it, that I was before starting my practice as a yogini. But I have gained so much wisdom and understanding that all the Therapy in the world could never have touched or unlocked.
And yet I hesitate today nervous, unsure, with so many mixed emotions,on my first day back  hoping to reignite the practice that has served me so well over time.
My practice that I dropped  unlovingly,  like a hot potato only 2 years  ago, as businesses, schools. peoples livelihoods and lives, came to a  screeching halt. 

My head is once again bursting with thoughts of ifs ands and buts.
But,,, I have come to the realization that although there are so many things that are out of our control.  I still have the opportunity to do things that are nourishing and productive and good for my spirit.  
With that realization, I have chosen to be here now, today, with a new community, with people I do not yet know and likely will never bond with as I did before.
I am hopeful and sure as the sun rises and sets each day. My spirit will be reignited once again as Adrienne has generously offered to be our guide bringing us lovingly back home to our center, our heart as one. Namaste!

Happy New Year!  HELP!  Would someone help me with some pointers on two parts of this particular practice I struggle with?

I mean, I can--but simultaneously, I am definitely putting pressure on my wrists.  What is a method for gradually building up whatever muscles I need to build up so I do this properly?

Hi, and Happy new year from Scotland.  I have been practising yoga for years but have recently been neglecting my (mostly) daily yoga because of chronic pain in my hip, groin and back.  I am only 51 but diagnosed with arthritis last year.  It was getting me down, because some of the yoga poses I used to find easy are now impossible or hard, and some poses now hurt to do.  But yoga was also good for me mentally, and I noticed it wasn't doing me any good by missing my daily yoga and mindfulness.  My breathing was becoming more shallow again, I was becoming more anxious and I had tension in my jaw etc.  I am now determined to start practising again and this 30 day challenge is going to be the thing that gets me back!  I am just going to accept I can't be as good as I once was and be easy on myself...if there is a pose I can't manage or it hurts, I will just do something else and enjoy it anyway.  I am going to be positive and focus on what I can do and not what I can't :)  Thank you Adriene, Namaste x

Yoga called me when I was 16 but I was not in need of it yet. As my body and mind began to age a bit I realized that I needed a cure but the gym life wasn‚Äôt for me. My joints and muscles were becoming sore on a regular basis due to constant hard labor. I was becoming fatigued mid day every day shortly after lunch. I needed help. I studied about the health benefits of regular practice and looked on YouTube and somehow stumbled across yoga with Adrian. Here I am almost two years strong in my practice and I can say that I‚Äôm a brand new being. I can endure hours of work with no pain in my body and my mind operates from both sides . I hit the mat early to start my day and it truly is a cheat code in this game of life. I‚Äôm done now. Lets flow people! Big shout out to all my fellow yogi‚Äôs who know that this is more than just simple poses. Its a framework that builds a better you.
